Can the euro be repaired?
Recently, German Finance Minister Scholz has put the option of Greece's exit from the euro on the table, and hopes to release a signal, namely that any member state cannot be exempt from the strict discipline of the currency union.
Actually, his plan has sparked a large discussion about the principles of the euro, euro governance model, and the basis for the existence of the euro.
Two weeks before Scholz's plan was put forward, European leaders had already noticed the report on the euro's future written by European Commission President von der Leyen and her colleagues from other EU institutions. But the new debate about Greece has made many decision-makers think it's necessary to return to the original starting point.
Meanwhile, citizens are questioning why they need to share the same currency?
Is this meaningful? Whether the future of Greece can be formed in a consistent manner?
Currency is like a country, establishing it requires a myth.
Traditional wisdom believes that Germany, in order to reunify, paid a political price to France during the Euro era.
In fact, German reunification was only the last step of a project that had already taken shape in the 1980s, solving a long-standing problem.
European governments strongly opposed floating exchange rates, considering it incompatible with a single market; at the same time, they did not want to maintain a currency mechanism dominated by the German central bank in the long term.
A truly European currency based on German principles seems to be the best solution.
Looking back, German reunification was more of a curse than a blessing.
When the exchange rate was fixed in 1999, Germany was overvalued, its economy was very difficult; France was undervalued, its economy was flourishing.
Over the next ten years, the imbalance gradually formed between the rising Germany and the countries with credit prosperity due to low interest rates.
And with the outbreak of the global financial crisis in 2008, these conditions became the cradle of a perfect storm.
No one knows what Europe will become without the euro.
Will the fixed exchange rate system continue or collapse?
Will the German mark be overvalued again?
Will countries reintroduce trade barriers and end the single market?
Will a real estate bubble rise in Spain?
Will government reform be more or less?
It is impossible to establish a reverse analysis baseline evaluation of the impact of the euro.
But this is no reason for complacency.
In the past 15 years, the economic performance of the euro area has been disappointing, and its political system must be held responsible for this.
What's really important is whether the common European currency is still important for the future.
This question is often avoided because the cost of exiting the euro is unimaginably high (and if the eurozone breaks down during a crisis and intensifies tensions between participating countries, the cost will be even higher)
Moreover, abolishing the euro may unleash the dark forces of nationalism and protectionism.
However, Kevin O'Rourke of Oxford University recently pointed out that this view is not comprehensive.
In logic, this is equivalent to suggesting that a couple should keep their marriage going because the cost of divorce is too high.
So, is the euro still meaningful?
Originally, people expected the euro to bring three major economic benefits.
They assumed that the monetary union would promote economic integration, consolidate Europe's long-term growth.
On the contrary, intra-eurozone trade and investment growth were lackluster, and the growth potential was actually weakened.
This is partly because national governments did not go further on the basis of monetary unity to build the eurozone into an economic superpower, but instead tried to preserve their remaining powers.
This may be in line with political logic, but it has no effect economically: Europe's large internal market is one of its major assets, and it cannot afford to waste the opportunity to strengthen the internal market.
Secondly, people hope that the euro will become one of the major international currencies (especially considering that very few countries can meet the necessary legal, market, and policy systems)
And according to the latest data from the European Central Bank, this hope has been basically achieved.
The international use of the euro ranks second only to the US dollar, which has achieved this achievement, helping Europe continue to influence the global economic order rather than becoming an irrelevant entity.
Thirdly, people (naively) think that institutions based on the euro can improve the overall quality of economic policy, as if the overall policy level of Europe is naturally higher than the policy level of individual countries.
After the 2008 global financial crisis, a severe test arrived: the euro area overestimated the fiscal dimension of the crisis and underestimated its financial dimension, thus its performance was not as good as that of the US and the UK.
If the euro is to bring about prosperity, further policy and institutional reforms are necessary.
However, setting up and implementing a schedule must have a broad and consistent understanding of the nature of the problem.
The persistent disputes over the Greek issue indicate that Europe is still far from achieving a consensus: member states have contradictory analyses of the root causes of the debt crisis, so the prescriptions they offer are also contradictory.
Richard Cooper of Harvard University once observed that, in the early stages of international cooperation in public health, the governance of global diseases was severely hampered by the different infectious patterns of each country.
Each country prefers joint action, but cannot form a consistent plan because they have different views on how infectious diseases can spread from one country to another.
This is the problem the eurozone is facing today.
Luckily, this problem is not insurmountable. The establishment of the European Stability Mechanism and the launch of the banking union, among other major reforms, have proven this point.
Even inconsistencies have not stopped the European Central Bank from taking decisive action, which shows that institutional governance is indeed important.
But it wasn't until recently that reforms and actions began, and they were only implemented under intense pressure from the severe crisis, which has made us realize the difficulty of reaching a consensus.
Europe cannot afford to drag its feet and pretend anymore.
The member states of the eurozone must establish a consistent schedule for governance and political reform, turning the monetary union into a prosperous engine, otherwise, they will only sink into repeated disputes and crises until citizens lose patience or the market loses trust.
Clarity is the prerequisite for serious discussion and grand reforms.
At present, all major parties have a duty to clarify what they consider indispensable, what they cannot accept, and what they are willing to exchange for what they want.
